Introduction/ purpose

When giving out home loans, it is in the best interest of everyone to acurately predict those who will make payments and those who will default. THe purpose of this project is to identify who should get a loan while avoiding turning down people who would be able to pay off a loan. This EDA notebook is an initial exploration of the data. The main question this is attempting to uncover is, â What is the best predictor or predictors of default?â It also looks at missing data and potential solutions, general correlations, and a brief exploration of joining with other data sets. questions to explore: What does the data look like? What is the data type? Is there a lot of missing data? Can it be deleted? Is it necessary? What seem to be the highest correlations and strongest predictors? Is any of our data weird, and how can we fix it? Does adding another data set help or create more noise? ## Load and view data

Data Description

The data consits of information about specific loan applicants. These variables include demographic, application, financial history, and repayment behaviors. Each row in the data represents the applicant/client. The TARGET is the most important variable in this data set as it is what we are trying to predict. The target is abinary variable if the applicant defaulted (1) or repaid the loan (0).There are also a few data sets outside training and testing that can be joined.

The target count shows us that 92% are non defualters. This is high enought that prediction methods would predict that nobody defaults.

This table helps to identify that variables that are most positiviely and negativley correlated. EXT source have the strongest negative correlation with the targe which means the higher the score the lower the default risk. These are very high predictors in this data set. Age(Days birth) has a negative correlation, older people may default less, and age could be a good predictor of default. This table also shows that there is a lot of multicollinearity going on. Some variables that have a very weak correlation are Flag_emp_phone and Days_last_phone_change.

Missing data discussion

Many of the missing varibles can be dropped. They have a very high percentage of missing data, and are likely very correlated with each other. All the correlations with the target for variables missing more than 60% are all very low, and are not linear predictors. With non-linear models they will likely create a lot of noise. I feel comfortable dropping all of these variables. It is important to look at the nature of the âmissing valuesâ. Is it missing, or is it just null? An example of where this could matter is children. Leaving the children blank canât just be removed because if the blank means that the applicant has 0 children, eliminating that isnât appropriate as it could be a big predictor.

Top Candidate Predictors of Default (by semantic importance)

  1. Debt-to-Income Ratio (or âtotal debt obligations / incomeâ)

    • A classic metric of capacity: if a large share of income is already committed to debt, the borrower has less room to absorb shocks, making default more likely.

  2. Loan-to-Value (LTV) or âamount applied / collateral or property valueâ

    • The higher the leverage (i.e.Â how much is borrowed relative to the assetâs value), the greater the risk (less cushion to absorb declines).

  3. Annuity / Monthly Payment Burden (i.e.Â âannuity / incomeâ or âmonthly payment / incomeâ)

    • How large is the repayment burden relative to earningsâif very high, more fragile.

  4. Number of Past Delinquencies / Payment Overdues (in bureau / installments)

    • Past behavior is a strong predictor: prior late payments or defaults indicate credit risk.

  5. Days Past Due (DPD) or Days Overdue Aggregates

    • The magnitude or frequency of days overdue (e.g.Â average, maximum) captures severity of past delinquency.

  6. Number of Credit Lines / Number of Loans Held

    • The more credit lines (especially active ones), the more exposure and complexity; also more potential correlation of stress across lines.

  7. Credit Utilization / Usage Ratio on Credit Cards

    • If a borrower uses near the limit of available credit, it suggests strain or lack of buffer.

  8. Length of Credit History / Vintage of Oldest Account

    • Longer history gives more signal; short history is riskier (less proven performance).

  9. Number of Previous Rejected Applications

    • Many rejections may indicate credit difficulty, overly aggressive applications, or weak creditworthiness.

  10. Employment Stability / Length (e.g.Â days employed, years in current job)

    • Stable employment suggests more reliable income; short or volatile employments raise risk.

  11. Age (or derived âage at loan endâ)

    • Very young or very old borrowers may have higher default risk (life-cycle risk, income instability, health, etc.).

  12. Number of Dependents / Family Size (or ânumber of childrenâ)

    • More dependents may stress finances, reducing disposable income for debt service.

  13. Housing Type / Home Ownership Status

    • Owning vs renting, mortgage burden, housing cost pressure all influence financial resilience.

  14. Region / Geographical Risk / Macro Indicator (e.g.Â regionâs unemployment)

    • External environment matters: in weaker economic areas, default risk is higher.

  15. External Credit Bureau Score / Credit Report Aggregates

    • If available, the borrowerâs broader credit bureau metrics (e.g.Â total credit debt, number of bureau accounts, credit score) are strong predictors.

  16. Delinquency Rate Ratio: (number of months overdue) / (number of months active)

    • A normalized measure of how âbadâ the credit history is relative to its length.

  17. Time Since Last Delinquency or Time Since Last Credit Activity

  18. Number of Open Installment Loans vs Revolving Loans

    • The mix of loan types matters: installment-heavy debt may be less flexible than revolving credit, so a heavy installment burden is riskier.

  19. Aggregate Defaults or Overdue Amounts from Bureau / Other Institutions

  20. Variance or Volatility in Payment Behavior (e.g.Â inconsistent payments over months)

    • Fluctuating payment patterns (large swings) suggest instability, which may presage future default.

Qualitative Rationale & Interactions

  • Behavioral / historical evidence (e.g.Â past delinquencies, DPD, aggregate overdue) tends to dominate because it is directly predictive of future default.
  • Capacity metrics (debt-to-income, annuity burden) calibrate how much stress a borrower can absorb.
  • Structural or constraint variables (number of loans, utilization, loanâtoâvalue, credit mix) create boundary risks.
  • Stability / resilience factors (employment length, credit history length, housing) provide âbuffersâ against shocks.
  • Macro / external context (region, external bureau data) capture systematic risk that is not captured in borrowerâs internal data alone.
